    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="section">
                <head>Letter 1: 6 June 1798</head>
                <lb/>
                <list rendition="#nostyle">
                    <item><hi rend="bold">Physical form:</hi> One sheet folded into 2 leaves (20 x
                        24.8 cm)</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">Cover:</hi> Miss Rickards / At M<hi rend="sup">rs</hi>
                        Hunts' / [<emph>in a different hand</emph>] Crescent [<emph>tear</emph>] /
                        near / Birmingham</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">PM:</hi> [<emph>inner circle</emph>] 6 [<emph>outer
                            circle</emph>] 98</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">WM:</hi> H &amp; T SALMON / [17]94</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">SM:</hi> Misc MS 4337</item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="letter">

                <opener>
                    <dateline>Dorking<note place="foot" resp="editors"> Dorking: a town in Surrey,
                            near Box Hill (so called from groves of box trees that grew on it). ALB
                            was at Dorking to be near her brother, JA, who spent the spring and
                            summer of 1798 there to recover from a serious illness. </note> June
                            6<hi rend="sup">th</hi></dateline>
                    <salute rendition="#indent1">My dear Lydia,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p rend="noCount" rendition="#firstline">I thank you for your pretty French letter,
                    which I would send back corrected if I had any frank;<note place="foot"
                        resp="editors"> frank: a cover signed by a member of Parliament, so that it
                        could be sent free of postage.</note> as it is, I will keep it till we
                    meet&#8212;Your observations on the history you have read are very just, &amp;
                    shew that you not only treasure up facts in your memory, but that your mind
                    receives the impressions those facts are calculated to make&#8212; Nothing
                    exercises the moral feelings more profitably than History. Whe[n] we study those
                    parts of science which relate to inanimate nature, our sagacity is called forth
                    &amp; our taste is gratified, but that lively interest is wanting which results
                    from contemplating the actions &amp; fortunes of our fellow creatures. On the
                    other hand when we enter with vivacity into the transactions which pass before
                    our eyes, our feelings are apt to be mingled with the bitterness of party or
                    tinged with private partialities &amp; resentments. In History alone nothing
                    checks the freedom of discussion [<emph>written over</emph>
                        “dissension”<emph>?</emph>] you may take the side of the Greeks or of the
                    Persians, <lb/><hi rendition="#catchword">without</hi><lb/></p>

                <p rend="noCount">[<emph>fol 1<hi rend="sup">v</hi></emph>] without giving offence
                    to any body, &amp; if you can pick up any anecdotes relative to the coterie of
                    Aspasia or the toilette of Semiramis they may be circulated without occasioning
                    any scandal&#8212;<note place="foot" resp="editors"> Aspasia of Miletus:
                        simultaneously a respected rhetorician and a socially dubious ‘hetaira’, her
                        relationship with Pericles was the source of gossip and invective; see
                        Athenaeus, <title level="m">The Deipnosophists</title> Book XIII, trans. C.
                        D. Yonge (1854). Semiramis: the legendary Assyrian-Babylonian wife of Onnes
                        and Ninus, the ruler of Assyria and Babylon. According to Diodorus Siculus,
                        Semiramis built the walls and gates of Babylon (<title level="m">The Library
                            of History</title>, Book II).</note> I hope you are all enjoying the
                    country as much as we do, but begging your pardon I doubt whether you have so
                    fine a one to enjoy, &amp; this I may say without any disparage^ment^ of yours
                    for the face of the country about Box Hill is I believe allowed to be one of the
                    finest in England. Add to this that its beautiful swells &amp; hollows are
                    improved to the best advantage in the numerous gentlemen’s seats which every
                    where embellish the prospect. Amongst these M<hi rend="sup">r</hi> Locke’s<note
                        place="foot" resp="editors"> William Lock(e) (1732–1810), "art connoisseur
                        and patron" (<title level="m">ODNB</title>).</note> has the preeminence for
                    the admirable disposition of the walks &amp; points of view, &amp; the artful
                    manner in which the different shades of green relieve one another so as to
                    produce the most picturesque effect. Indeed modern English Gardening is the art
                    of Landscape painting only the artist uses real trees &amp; turf &amp; water
                    instead of canvass &amp; a box of colours but he considers every effect of light
                    &amp; shade the disposition of every tree &amp; almost of every bough. His
                        keeping,<note place="foot" resp="editors"> "keeping": In painting, "the
                        maintenance of the proper relation between the representation of nearer and
                        more distant objects in a picture" (<title level="m">OED</title>, <title
                            level="a">Keeping,</title> 9.a).</note> his foregrounds &amp; his
                    back-grounds are all disposed by the same rules of art which the Painter
                    observes. M<hi rend="sup">r</hi> Locke had a consultation of Painters to
                    determine in what spot of the grounds his house <del rend="overstrike"
                        >should</del> would be built to most advantage&#8212;I wish you would give
                    me </p>

                <p rend="noCount">[<emph>fol 2<hi rend="sup">r</hi></emph>] [your] opinion in your
                    next letter <hi rend="underline">what constitutes that beauty, in a landscape
                        with which we are all so much charmed</hi>; how much of it is owing to
                    colour, to form, to contrast, to motion &amp;c&#8212;This is a very good country
                    for botanizing. We have had several specimens of the various species of the
                    Orchis, many of which (formed it should seem in the sportiveness of nature) bear
                    a whimsical resemblance to some animal or part of animal. There is the <hi
                        rend="underline">bee Orchis</hi> &amp; the [<emph>tear</emph>] <hi
                        rend="underline">Orchis</hi>, each of which [m]ight deceive the eye with
                        [<emph>rese</emph>]mblance of those insects whose name they
                        [bear] &amp; there is another, the root of which is exactly
                    like a child’s, or if you will, a fairy’s <hi rend="underline">hand</hi>. I
                    hardly know what to tell you about my Brother; a while ago we thought him
                    mending, he is just now not so well, <del rend="overstrike">vicica</del>
                    Vicissitudes more anxious than uniform illness! He seems to take <del
                        rend="overstrike">com</del>fort in our company. I will wait therefore till I
                    have another letter fr[<emph>heavy crossout</emph>]<del rend="overstrike"
                        >before</del> I fix our return, as it is possible <hi rend="underline"
                        >you</hi> may have plans which may delay you[.] Remember me affectionately
                    to M<hi rend="sup">rs</hi> Rickards &amp; Miss H.<note place="foot"
                        resp="editors"> "Miss H": Miss Harrup or Harrop, mentioned several times in
                        these letters but not identified. On 9 June 1802 she took tea with the
                        Barbaulds (RB, Diary", 1–22 June 1802. MS. Estate of Lady Rodgers. Cited
                        hereafter as 'RB, Diary.').</note> tell M<hi rend="sup">rs</hi> Rickards she
                    has had an escape of increasing her family by the servant she dismissed . She
                    has acknowledged to M<hi rend="sup">rs</hi> Carr<note place="foot"
                        resp="editors"> "Mrs Carr": Frances Carr, of Hampstead, whose family were
                        friends with the Barbaulds.</note> that she is five months gone with child.
                    Excuse me [for not] having written sooner, &amp; </p>

                <closer>
                        <salute rendition="#indent6">believe [<emph>tear</emph>] Lydia Your very
                                    aff<hi rend="sup">te</hi> friend</salute>
                        <signed rendition="#indent7">AL Barbauld</signed>                 
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
